root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3918</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00NQ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00NQ.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Strong induction as <fr:link
href="jms-00NP.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00NP">well-founded induction</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The “strong” or “complete” induction principle for natural numbers states that for any subset <fr:tex>S\subseteq  \mathbb {N}</fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex>\forall  x\in  \mathbb {N}\mathpunct {.} x\in  S</fr:tex> if and only if we have <fr:tex>0\in  S</fr:tex> and, for any <fr:tex>n\in  \mathbb {N}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>m\in  S</fr:tex> for all <fr:tex>m&lt;n</fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex>n\in  S</fr:tex>. This is precisely the statement of <fr:link
href="jms-00NP.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00NP">well-founded induction</fr:link> for the <fr:link
href="jms-00NM.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00NM">strictly less-than relation</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
